9.1 Ensemble method: Bagging(or bootstrap aggregation)

    1. Draw bootstrap samples from your data.

    2. From each bootstrap sample, build a decision tree model.

    3. The final model is the average of all the individual decision trees.

Example: Spambase data

loglikelihood <- function(y, py) {
  pysmooth <- ifelse(py == 0, 1e-12, 
                     ifelse(py == 1, 1 - 1e-12, py))
  sum(y*log(pysmooth) + (1 - y)*log(1 - pysmooth))
}

accuracyMeasures <- function(pred, truth, name = "model") {
  dev.norm <- -2*loglikelihood(as.numeric(truth), pred)/length(pred)
  ctable <- table(truth = truth,
                  pred = (pred > 0.5))  # cutoff = 0.5
  print(ctable)
  accuracy <- sum(diag(ctable))/sum(ctable)
  precision <- ctable[2,2]/sum(ctable[,2])
  recall <- ctable[2,2]/sum(ctable[2,])
  f1 <- precision*recall
  data.frame(model = name, accuracy = accuracy, f1 = f1, dev.norm)
}
  • Decision tree

  • Bagging decision trees
ntrain <- dim(spamTrain)[1]
n <- ntrain
ntree <- 100 
samples <- sapply(1:ntree, 
                  FUN = function(iter){
                      sample(1:ntrain, size = n, replace = TRUE)
                    }
                  )
treelist <- lapply(1:ntree, 
                   FUN = function(iter){
                       samp <- samples[,iter]
                       rpart(spamFormula, spamTrain[samp,])
                     }
                  )

predict.bag <- function(treelist, newdata) {
  preds <- sapply(1:length(treelist), 
                  FUN = function(iter) {
                      predict(treelist[[iter]], newdata = newdata)
                    }
                  )
  predsums <- rowSums(preds)
  predsums/length(treelist)
}

accuracyMeasures(predict.bag(treelist, newdata = spamTrain), 
                 spamTrain$spam == "spam", 
                 name = "bagging, training")
##               model  accuracy        f1  dev.norm
## 1 bagging, training 0.9242095 0.8128602 0.4696682
accuracyMeasures(predict.bag(treelist, newdata = spamTest), 
                 spamTest$spam == "spam",
                 name = "bagging, test")
##           model  accuracy        f1  dev.norm
## 1 bagging, test 0.9126638 0.7819273 0.5256847

9.2 Ensemble method: Random forest

  • Random forest observation feature resampling

    1. Draw a bootstrapped sample from the training data

    2. For each sample, grows a decision tree, and at each node of the tree

      1. Randomly draws a subset of \(m\) variables from the \(p\) total features that are available

      2. Picks the best variable and the best split from that set of \(m(\ll p)\) variables

      3. Continues until the tree is fully grown

  • \(m = \sqrt{p}\)

    • () \(p=100\) \(m = 10\)

    • feature tree tree dependence

    • Regression \(m = p/3\)

  • Variable importance

    • Feature tree Gini impurity variable importance

9.3 Ensemble method: Boosting

  • bootstrap sample observation

  • observation obs.

9.3.1 Adaboost

    1. \(w_i=1/n\) \(m=0\)

    2. Set \(m \leftarrow m+1\). \(G_m(x)\)

    3. \[ {\rm err}_m = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n w_iI(y_i \neq G_m(x_i) )}{\sum_{i=1}^n w_i} \]

    4. () \[ \alpha_m = \frac{1}{2}\log\left(\frac{1-{\rm err}_m}{{\rm err}_m}\right) \]

    5. : obs. \(e^{\alpha_m}\) obs. \(e^{-\alpha_m}\) , 1 normalize

    6. Step 2 - 5 \(M\) \(M\)

    7. : \[ G(x) = {\rm sgn}\left(\sum_{m=1}^M \alpha_m G_m(x)\right) \]

n.tr <- nrow(spamTrain)
n.test <- nrow(spamTest)
w <- rep(1, n.tr)/n.tr
M <- 20
G.tr <- matrix(NA, M, n.tr)
G.test <- matrix(NA, M, n.test)
alpha <- rep(NA, M)
for ( m in 1:M ) {
  treemodel <- rpart(spamFormula, data = spamTrain, weights = w)
  pred.tr <- predict(treemodel, newdata = spamTrain) >= 0.5
  pred.test <- predict(treemodel, newdata = spamTest) >= 0.5
  p.tr <- rep("non-spam", n.tr)
  p.test <- rep("non-spam", n.test)
  p.tr[pred.tr] <- "spam"
  p.test[pred.test] <- "spam"
  G.tr[m, ] <- p.tr
  G.test[m, ] <- p.test
  err <- sum(w[p.tr != spamTrain$spam])/sum(w)
  alpha[m] <- .5*log(min(1 - err, 1 - 1e-6)/max(err, 1e-6))
  w[p.tr == spamTrain$spam] <- w[p.tr == spamTrain$spam]*exp(-alpha[m])
  w[p.tr != spamTrain$spam] <- w[p.tr != spamTrain$spam]*exp(alpha[m])
  w <- w/sum(w)
}
print(alpha)
##  [1] 1.15957929 0.83580492 0.79249037 0.78060177 0.80883428 0.65320312
##  [7] 0.71342301 0.61586531 0.65357605 0.69715075 0.52724927 0.54355108
## [13] 0.46599207 0.54445722 0.36774458 0.33212760 0.30622458 0.17263570
## [19] 0.06294804 0.36450996
alpha.tr <- matrix(alpha, M, n.tr, byrow = TRUE)
alpha.test <- matrix(alpha, M, n.test, byrow = TRUE)

accuracyMeasures(colSums(alpha.tr*(2*(G.tr == "spam") - 1)) > 0,   
                 spamTrain$spam == "spam",
                 name = "adaboost, train")
##             model accuracy        f1  dev.norm
## 1 adaboost, train 0.989621 0.9738495 0.5735623
accuracyMeasures(colSums(alpha.test*(2*(G.test == "spam") - 1)) > 0,   
                 spamTest$spam == "spam",
                 name = "adaboost, test")
##            model  accuracy        f1 dev.norm
## 1 adaboost, test 0.9366812 0.8421378 3.499126

9.3.2 Functional gradient boosting algorithm

  • Friedmann et al. (2000), Friedmann (2001): , \[ E \left\{L(f({\mathbf X}), Y)\right\} \] \(f\)

  • Empirical version: \[ n^{-1}\sum_{i=1}^n L(f(x_i), y_i) \]

  • Gradient descent algorithm

    • (loss function) \(L(f_\theta({\mathbf X}), Y)\), (learning rate) \(\eta\) \[ \theta^{(1)} = \theta^{(0)} - \eta\cdot\frac{\partial}{\partial\theta}E L(f_\theta({\mathbf X}), Y) \]

  • Generic FGD algorithm

    1. Initialize \({\hat f}^{(0)}(\cdot)\) with an offset value \[ {\hat f}^{(0)}(\cdot) = \arg\min_c \,\,\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n L(c, y_i) \] and set \(m=0\).

    2. Set \(m = m+1\). Compute the negative gradient \(-\frac{\partial}{\partial f} L(f, y)\) and evaluate at \({\hat f}^{(m-1)}(x_i)\): \[ U_i = -\frac{\partial}{\partial f}L(f, y_i)\Big|_{f = {\hat f}^{(m-1)}(x_i)},\quad i=1,2,...,n \]

    3. Fit \(U_i\)s to \(x_i\)s by the base procedure (e.g.regression). \[ (x_i, U_i)_{i=1}^n \stackrel{\rm base\,\, procedure}{\longrightarrow} \hat{g}^{(m)}(\cdot) \] \(\hat{g}^{(m)}(\cdot)\) can be viewed as an approximation of the negative gradient vector.

    4. Update: \[ {\hat f}^{(m)}(\cdot) = {\hat f}^{(m-1)}(\cdot) + \eta\, {\hat g}^{(m)}(\cdot) \]

    5. Iterate steps 2 to 4 until \(m = M\).

  • Adaboost \(L(f, y) = \exp(-(2y-1)f)\) (Breiman, 1998, 1999)

:

  • gbm 
library(gbm)
## Loaded gbm 2.1.5
boostedTree <- gbm(spamFormula, data = spamTrain, 
                   distribution = "bernoulli", 
                   cv.folds = 5, n.trees = 5000)

  • distribution : \(L\)

    • gaussian (squared error), laplace (absolute loss), bernoulli (logistic regression for 0-1 outcomes), multinomial (classification when there are more than 2 classes), adaboost (the AdaBoost exponential loss for 0-1 outcomes), and so on
best.iter <- gbm.perf(boostedTree, method = "cv") 

pred <- predict(boostedTree, spamTrain, best.iter)
print(ctableTrain <- table(pred > 0, spamTrain$spam == "spam"))
##        
##         FALSE TRUE
##   FALSE  2451   96
##   TRUE     59 1537
print(accuracyTrain <- sum(diag(ctableTrain))/sum(ctableTrain))
## [1] 0.9625875
pred <- predict(boostedTree, spamTest, best.iter)
print(ctableTest <- table(pred > 0, spamTest$spam == "spam"))
##        
##         FALSE TRUE
##   FALSE   268   15
##   TRUE     10  165
print(accuracyTest <- sum(diag(ctableTest))/sum(ctableTest))
## [1] 0.9454148

9.3.3 XGBoost

  • Extreme gradient boosting

  • Gradient boosting

  • , imbalance , variable importance 

library(xgboost)

spamTrainLabel <- 1*(spamTrain$spam == "spam")
XTrain <- data.matrix(spamTrain[, spamVars])
DTrain <- xgb.DMatrix(data = XTrain, label = spamTrainLabel)  

spamTestLabel <- 1*(spamTest$spam == "spam")
XTest <- data.matrix(spamTest[, spamVars])
DTest <- xgb.DMatrix(data = XTest, label = spamTestLabel)

watchlist <- list(train = DTrain, test = DTest)
bst <- xgb.train(data = DTrain,
                 nrounds = 3,
                 watchlist = watchlist,
                 objective = "binary:logistic")    
## [1]  train-error:0.066377    test-error:0.076419 
## [2]  train-error:0.063963    test-error:0.076419 
## [3]  train-error:0.056964    test-error:0.069869

  • objective

    • reg:linear: linear regression (Default).

    • reg:logistic: logistic regression.

    • binary:logistic: logistic regression for binary classification. Output probability.

    • binary:logitraw: logistic regression for binary classification, output score before logistic transformation.

    • num_class set the number of classes. To use only with multiclass objectives.

    • multi:softmax set xgboost to do multiclass classification using the softmax objective. Class is represented by a number and should be from 0 to num_class - 1.

    • multi:softprob same as softmax, but prediction outputs a vector of ndata * nclass elements, which can be further reshaped to ndata, nclass matrix. The result contains predicted probabilities of each data point belonging to each class.

  • &
